<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06064121 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06064121 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SYRIA; IRAN; AID; US; TERRORISM; END  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Syrian President Hafez Assad, long named by the United States as a majorsponsor of terrorism, acted to restrain terrorists from attacking Westerntargets during the Persian Gulf war after a personal appeal from PresidentBush, Secretary of State James Baker said Sunday.;    Other officials saidIran and even Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi played &quot;a surprisingly responsiblerole&quot; in urging their allies not to attack Western interests during the war.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SYRIA, IRAN HELP U.S. RESTRAIN TERRORISTS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  See related articles on pages 1a and 9A-12AWar in the Gulf  </MEMO><TEXT>     The unusual stand by three of the Middle East's most radical regimes mayhave been a major factor in heading off anti-American terrorism during thesix-week war, in part because it meant that pro-Iraqi terrorists couldn'tcount on a safe haven in those countries, terrorism experts said.;    In thecase of Syria, it also gave U.S. officials new hope for a more productiverelationship with Assad after a decade-long chill, much of it arising fromSyria's suspected role in such terrorist attacks as the 1983 bombing of theU.S. Marine barracks in Beirut, Lebanon. Syria is also the headquarters of thePalestinian terrorist group suspected of carrying out the December 1988bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie, Scotland.;    Recently, however,Baker said, &quot;there has been some movement . . . and Syria has taken someaction.&quot;;    &quot;Syria is serious when it says, 'We are going to see what we cando about (terrorism), because we are interested in improving our relationshipwith the West,' &quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Los Angeles Times  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Washington  </CITY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  SAN JOSE MERCURY NEWS  </NAME><PUBDATE>   9103